{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518775"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:07:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:07:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12948"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12948"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.26,0.1,0.31,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53902"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5386"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12948"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39364"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9721"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16171"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53902"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 31-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a 10-month history of frequent bowel movements. She reports that her stools are occasionally pale, greasy and difficult to flush. She experiences crampy abdominal pain often, but only rarely has nausea or vomiting. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She reports no recent antibiotic use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Laboratory studies reveal a haemoglobin level of 99 g/L (125\u2013185) and a white cell count of 14.0\u00a0x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0\u201311.0). Colonoscopy reveals friable mucosa with oedema and mucosal nodularity over the terminal ileum and colon. Biopsy findings show transmural inflammation with granulomas.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely long-term complication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Toxic megacolon","Primary sclerosing cholangitis","Dermatitis herpetiformis","Osteoporosis","Pseudomembranous colitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the patient\u0027s symptoms, laboratory results, and colonoscopy findings, the most likely diagnosis is Crohn\u0027s disease (CD). CD is a chronic inflammatory condition that can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from the mouth to the rectum. Common symptoms of CD include crampy abdominal pain, diarrhoea, fatigue, and weight loss. The majority of diarrhoea in CD is without gross blood, and steatorrhea can occur due to loss of bile salts. CD can lead to malabsorption, which manifests as complications such as protein calorie malnutrition, hypocalcaemia, and deficiencies in vitamins (e.g., vitamin B12, folate, or iron).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with longstanding CD are at an increased risk of developing \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteoporosis\u003C/strong\u003E (prevalence ~18%-42%). The pathogenesis of osteoporosis in CD involves disease-related inflammatory activity and deficiencies in vitamin D and calcium due to malabsorption. Furthermore, CD is often treated with steroids, which also increase osteoporosis risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic megacolon\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by nonobstructive dilation of the colon associated with systemic toxicity, is classically associated with ulcerative colitis, rather than CD. It is still possible for patients with CD to develop this rare (incidence ~1-5%) but potentially deadly complication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC)\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic cholestatic liver disease characterised by inflammation and fibrosis of the biliary tree. It is also classically associated with ulcerative colitis, rather than CD. Around 90% of patients with PSC have concomitant UC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatitis herpetiformis\u003C/strong\u003E is a common extraintestinal manifestation of coeliac disease, characterised by intensely pruritic papules and vesicles in grouped arrangements. Although the patient\u0027s presentation may raise the possibility of coeliac disease, the endoscopy findings are more suggestive of CD. Pyoderma gangrenosum and erythema nodosum are the most common cutaneous findings in patients with inflammatory bowel disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomembranous colitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe inflammation of the inner lining of the large intestine, typically caused by \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection, which often occurs when antibiotic therapy disrupts the normal gut flora. It is not a common complication of CD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Malabsorption is a prevalent issue in inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) and can give rise to complications such as protein-calorie malnutrition, vitamin deficiencies, and metabolic bone disease.","Patients with longstanding Crohn\u0027s disease are at increased risk of developing osteoporosis due to inflammatory activity, malabsorption, and steroid treatment."],"references":["Ali T, Lam D, Bronze MS, Humphrey MB. Osteoporosis in inflammatory bowel disease. Am H Med. 2009 Jul 1;122(7):599-604. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2894700/","Ott C, Sch\u00f6lmerich J. Extraintestinal manifestations and complications in IBD. Nat Rev Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2013 Oct;10(10):585-95. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/nrgastro.2013.117"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39364"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12948"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39364"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-27T15:56:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-27T15:57:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5386"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53902"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level 